<p>The royal flush is a case of the straight flush. It can be formed 4 ways=
 (one for each suit), giving it a probability of 0.000154% and odds of 649,=
739&nbsp;: 1.
</p><p>When ace-low straights and ace-low straight flushes are not counted,=
 the probabilities of each are reduced: straights and straight flushes each=
 become 9/10 as common as they otherwise would be.  The 4 missed straight f=
lushes become flushes and the 1,020 missed straights become no pair.
</p><p>Note that since suits have no relative value in poker, two hands can=
 be considered identical if one hand can be transformed into the other by s=
wapping suits.  For example, the hand <b>3=E2=99=A3 7=E2=99=A3 8=E2=99=A3 Q=
=E2=99=A0 A=E2=99=A0</b> is identical to <b><span style=3D"color:red;">3=E2=
=99=A6 7=E2=99=A6 8=E2=99=A6 Q=E2=99=A5 A=E2=99=A5</span></b> because repla=
cing all of the clubs in the first hand with diamonds and all of the spades=
 with hearts produces the second hand.  So eliminating identical hands that=
 ignore relative suit values, there are only 134,459 distinct hands.
</p><p>The number of distinct poker hands is even smaller.  For example, <b=
>3=E2=99=A3 7=E2=99=A3 8=E2=99=A3 Q=E2=99=A0 A=E2=99=A0</b> and <b><span st=
yle=3D"color:red;">3=E2=99=A6</span> 7=E2=99=A3 <span style=3D"color:red;">=
8=E2=99=A6 Q=E2=99=A5 A=E2=99=A5</span></b> are not identical hands when ju=
st ignoring suit assignments because one hand has three suits, while the ot=
her hand has only two=E2=80=94that difference could affect the relative val=
ue of each hand when there are more cards to come.  However, even though th=
e hands are not identical from that perspective, they still form equivalent=
 poker hands because each hand is an <b>A-Q-8-7-3</b> high card hand.  Ther=
e are 7,462 distinct poker hands.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"7-card_poker_hands">7-card =
poker hands</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Poker_probability&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section:=
 7-card poker hands"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bra=
cket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In some popular variations of poker such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Texas_hold_%27em" title=3D"Texas hold 'em">Texas hold 'em</a>,=
 the most widespread poker variant overall,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poker_probability#cite_=
note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup> a player uses the best five-card poker hand out of seven=
 cards.
</p><p>The frequencies are calculated in a manner similar to that shown for=
 5-card hands,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poker_probability#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> except add=
itional complications arise due to the extra two cards in the 7-card poker =
hand.  The total number of distinct 7-card hands is <span class=3D"mwe-math=
-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe=
-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.or=
g/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\textstyle {52 \choose 7}=3D133{,}784{,}560=
}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"false" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mrow>
            <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-OPEN">
              <mo maxsize=3D"1.2em" minsize=3D"1.2em">(</mo>
            </mrow>
            <mfrac linethickness=3D"0">
              <mn>52</mn>
              <mn>7</mn>
            </mfrac>
            <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-CLOSE">
              <mo maxsize=3D"1.2em" minsize=3D"1.2em">)</mo>
            </mrow>
          </mrow>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mn>133,784,560</mn>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\textstyle {52 \choose 7}=
=3D133{,}784{,}560}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/c16f50c712f4abd4941997615f0226e1d893399d" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -1.171ex; width:18.628ex; height:3.509ex;" alt=3D"{\textstyle {52 \=
choose 7}=3D133{,}784{,}560}"></span>.  It is notable that the probability =
of a no-pair hand is <i>lower</i> than the probability of a one-pair or two=
-pair hand.
</p><p>The Ace-high straight flush or royal flush is slightly more frequent=
 (4324) than the lower straight flushes (4140 each) because the remaining t=
wo <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Playing_card" title=3D"Playing =
card">cards</a> can have any value; a King-high straight flush, for example=
, cannot have the Ace of its suit in the hand (as that would make it ace-hi=
gh instead).
</p>
